THOUGHT: Let me examine the condition more carefully. The lambda returns true if the instruction is not in SeenInstrs and not skipped. For header phis, we want to return false only if they are in SeenInstrs or skipped; otherwise, they should be considered not in SeenInstrs and not skipped, so return true. So the condition should be:

if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())
  return !(!SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true));

Which simplifies to:

if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())
  return SeenInstrs.contains(&I) || CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);

But that would return true if the phi is in SeenInstrs or skipped, which would cause the outer any_of to return true, indicating an additional simplification. That's not what we want. We want to ignore phis that are in SeenInstrs or skipped, and only consider phis that are not in SeenInstrs and not skipped as additional simplifications.

Actually, the lambda returns true when an instruction is an additional simplification. So for a header phi that is not in SeenInstrs and not skipped, it should return true. For a header phi that is in SeenInstrs or skipped, it should return false. So the condition should be:

if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())
  return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);

But note that the original code returns false for all header phis, which is equivalent to saying header phis are never additional simplifications. We want to change that to only ignore header phis that are accounted for.

Let me implement this change.

```bash
sed -i 's/      if (isa<PHINode>(&I) \&\& BB == TheLoop->getHeader())/      if (isa<PHINode>(&I) \&\& BB == TheLoop->getHeader())\n        return !SeenInstrs.contains(\&I) \&\& !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(\&I, true);/' /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
```

